The paper focuses on a framework for authoring and consuming time-based media using printed codes and mobile applications. This involves aspects of human-computer interaction (cs.HC) in terms of designing a system that is easy to use and personalized for the viewer. The use of 2D and 3D geometric transformations, color transformation, and annotation suggests a focus on computer graphics (cs.GR) and computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also mentions applications in cultural heritage, education, creative art, and design, which could fall under multimedia (cs.MM) and augmented reality (cs.AR).
